Henry Ciuci (April 25, 1903 – January 1986) was an American professional &lt;a href="golf"&gt;golf&lt;/a&gt;er. He won six official &lt;a href="PGA%20Tour"&gt;PGA Tour&lt;/a&gt; events in the late 1920s and early 1930s, and was one of the Tour's most successful performers between 1928 and 1931.
His best finish in a &lt;a href="Men%27s%20major%20golf%20championships"&gt;major championship&lt;/a&gt; was a tie for fifth place in the &lt;a href="1924%20PGA%20Championship"&gt;1924 PGA Championship&lt;/a&gt;. His best effort in the &lt;a href="US%20Open%20%28golf%29"&gt;U.S. Open&lt;/a&gt; was a sixth place tie in &lt;a href="1928%20U.S.%20Open%20%28golf%29"&gt;1928&lt;/a&gt;. He finished T25 in the &lt;a href="1934%20Masters%20Tournament"&gt;1934 Masters Tournament&lt;/a&gt;.
Golf career.
Ciuci won two Tour events in 1928, and scored two second-place finishes. He had 11 finishes in the top-10 and 15 in the top-25 that season. In 1929, he won one Tour event, finished third three times, had eight finishes in the top-10 and 17 in the top-25. He had his best season in 1931, winning three times, one of which was the inaugural &lt;a href="Connecticut%20Open%20%28golf%29"&gt;Connecticut Open&lt;/a&gt;. Also in 1931, he finished third twice, had eight finishes in the top-10 and 10 in the top-25. For his career, in addition to the six wins, Ciuci is credited with 53 top-10 finishes and 85 finishes in the top-25.
